    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-09-13T03:54:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-09-13T03:54:00-05:00" n="952"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d952">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890F.515/40: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Saudi Arabia</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Moose</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jidda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-09-13T12:00:00+03:06"
                            >September 13, 1943—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 4:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>122. My 117, September 9, 7 p.m. British Minister finally left Jidda for Riyadh
                    this morning taking with him a draft law prepared some time ago for the emission
                    of paper currency in Saudi Arabia and he intends to discuss matter with King.
                    The plan does not contemplate the establishment of a bank. British Minister can
                    hardly arrive at Riyadh before evening September 15 and probably any discussions
                    on subject would take place a day or two after his arrival.</p>
                <p>In view of the penultimate paragraph of the Department’s 41, August 3, 9 p.m.,
                    Department may wish me to suggest to the King through Hamid Suleiman, Acting
                    Minister of Finance and brother of Abdullah Suleiman, or other available high
                    official, that no definite commitment be made with regard to paper currency
                    before completion of the formalities connected with lease-lending of silver to
                    Saudi Arabia.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Cairo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moose</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
